ptian perspective, and examine the reception in Rome of Egyptian culture, especially of its religion and architecture. They discuss films about her, and consider what inspired Egyptomania in early modern art. Together, these essays illuminate Cleopatra’s legacy and illustrate how it has been used and reused through the centuries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aQueenszEgyptvBiography. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aancient egypt religion.  aancient egypt.  aancient egyptian architecture.  aancient egyptian rulers.  aancient egyptian women.  aancient history.  aancient pharaoh.  aancient roman politics.  aancient rome.  aclassical studies.  acleopatra afterlife.  acleopatra and egypt.  acleopatra and rome.  acleopatra love potions.  acleopatra vii.  aearly modern art.  aegyptian culture.  aegyptian religion.  aegyptomania.  ahistoric women figures.  aimperial rome.  alife of cleopatra.  apolitical history.  aroman history.  arome and egypt.  awomen in history.1 aAshton, Sally-Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurran, Brian A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeMaria-Smith, Margaret Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGurval, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiles, Margaret M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiles, Margaret M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMontserrat, Dominic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPucci, Giuseppe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowland, Ingrid D., e